defaultSUMMARYdefault&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn 2011 the Stoke by Nayland Academy Trust (SbNAT) applied to the DfE to open an 11-16 school in Stoke by Nayland (a village in South Suffolk). This bid was
default unsuccessful. The Seckford Foundation then applied to the DfE in 2012 to open an 11-16 school on the same site. This bid was also unsuccessful.
default defaultStoke by Nayland is in a part of Suffolk with a significant surplus of secondary-school places. 
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCOMPASS formed
default in response to a free school proposal in Stoke by Nayland, in order to promote open debate about the issues that would arise should the free school bid be successful. Both SbNAT and the Seckford Foundation refused to engage in public debate with us.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCOMPA
defaultSS submitted a thorough explanation of our grounds for opposing the school to the DfE in both 2011 and 2012, and requested a meeting to discuss these further. On both occasions we were advised that there was no opportunity to raise our concerns with the Df
defaultE until or unless the bids reached the 
default‘
defaultpre-opening
default’
default 
defaultstage. We considered this a weakness in the free schools application process.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCOMPASS
default’
defaults view was (and remains) that it is not possible to establish a new school in an area with a large surplus of school 
defaultplaces without it having a negative impact on existing provision and the wider community. Therefore the application process should include, at an early stage, the promotion of open public debate and an opportunity for those opposing the proposal to be hear
defaultd. Instead, there was a culture of secrecy about both the free school proposals and the application process. This was perpetuated by the DfE
default’
defaults refusal to meet with us and hear our concerns. 
defaultBACKGROUND AND HISTORYdefaultLocal Context and Stoke by Nayland Academydefault Trustdefault&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe proposed closure of middle schools in Suffolk (a process known locally as the Schools Organisation Review or SOR) coincided from 2010 with the opportunity for parent-led groups to apply to the DfE to open a Free School. This led to a number of f
defaultree school applications in the county for 11-16 schools, all in small towns where there was some parental opposition to the closure of the middle schools. In 2011 a parent-led group, the Stoke by Nayland Academy Trust (SbNAT), applied to open an 11-16 scho
defaultol in Stoke by Nayland from September 2013, intending to use the site of the middle school in that village which was set to close in July 2013.  
defaultEstablishment and make-up of COMPASSdefault&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCOMPASS was formed in response to that application. We were concerned abo
defaultut the absence of informed debate about the benefits and potential risks of a new 11-16 free school in Stoke by Nayland, and formed COMPASS as a campaign group in order to promote open debate on the issue.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCOMPASS was a single-issue community campaign group with no political affiliation 
default–
default 
defaultthough some individual members and supporters do hold a range of strong political views. It had a core organising group of eight: six parents with children at GCUS and loca
defaultl primary schools, one of whom was also a governor at GCUS and another of whom was on the equivalent of the PTA. Two further members were teachers at GCUS, one of whom is also a Liberal Democrat councillor.
defaultCampaigndefault&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCOMPASS held a number of public events a
defaultt local schools 
default–
default 
defaultboth formal meetings and informal drop-in sessions, and provided information which was publicised on our website and via social media, and circulated to parents by the schools in the GCUS pyramid (with permission from the headteachers inv
defaultolved). 
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultHaving gained local support from parents and community-members in the area that would have been affected by the opening of a new school, COMPASS organised a petition opposing the free school. This was submitted to the DfE, alongside a document out
defaultlining the reasons for our opposition to the proposed free school, to coincide with the deadline for Free School applications. 
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe proposal by SbNAT was rejected by the DfE.
defaultSeckford Foundation Proposaldefault&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn 2012 SbNAT ceded control of the bid for an 11-16 
defaultschool in Stoke by Nayland to the Seckford Foundation (who had also bid to open two more free schools in Suffolk 
default–
default 
defaultBeccles and Saxmundham). COMPASS continued to provide opportunities for local debate on the proposed free school. We again submitted a compre
defaulthensive document to the DfE outlining our opposition to the proposed school, with a request to meet the DfE and discuss our concerns in greater depth. The proposal by the Seckford Foundation in 2012 was also rejected by the DfE.
defaultOutcomedefault&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe two application
defaults to run an 11-16 Free School in Stoke by Nayland were both rejected. COMPASS as a campaign group is therefore no longer active, although members of the group continue to be actively involved in schools in the area.
