defaultThe lack of transparency or opportunity for open public debate in the free school application process at conceptual and application stages (paragraphs 18-24);
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe 
defaultimpact that opening a new 11-16 school in our area would have on existing schools and the Schools Reorganisation already underway in Suffolk (paragraphs 25-30).
defaultEducational Offerdefault&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultBoth proposers sought to provide a small secondary school and, in their focus
default on academic subjects, struggled to avoid the association that their school would be selective. As such their proposals were divisive. The proposals were carefully marketed and drew heavily on anger amongst some parents about the proposed closure of the mi
defaultddle school, and claims that could not be substantiated (such as the value of small schools). Because of the lack of public debate, it was not possible to test out these assumptions in a calm and measured way to enable parents to make a fully informed choi
defaultce about what was on offer.  
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThere were a number of other concerns about the actual school offer in both years, but these are not explored in this document as the proposals were unsuccessful.
defaultLack of Transparencydefault&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultNeither SbNAT nor the Seckford Foundation 
defaultmade their business cases for the proposed school available to the public. Neither organisation provided information about the numbers registering for the proposed schools, despite requests to do so. It was therefore impossible for the bidders to respond a
defaultdequately to the concerns of local parents about the educational offer they would be in a position to make should their application have been successful, or about the impact that the proposed school would have had on existing schools.
defaultLack of claritydefault&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultFrom 
defaultthe outset in 2010 it was also difficult to discern the difference between local anger at the closure of middle schools and local support for the proposed free schools. Free schools were publicised as extending choice following the closure of middle school
defaults, even though the closure of middle schools did not reduce choice of school, simply the year groups at which pupils change schools. It is therefore possible that proposers and DfE may have colluded in allowing those opposing closure of the middle schools 
defaultto feel 
default–
default 
defaultmistakenly 
default–
default 
defaultthat their voice had been heard.
defaultLack of accountability of the proposers to the local communitydefault&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSbNAT refused to enter into public debate with COMPASS, and instead sought to denigrate our campaign. The Seckford Foundation did provide
default communications events for parents to find out about the proposed school and to invite registrations, but refused to acknowledge the existence of local opposition or to enter into open dialogue about the proposed free school. Both argued 
default–
default 
defaultand the free sch
defaultool application process supported this position 
default–
default 
defaultthat the free school proposals could be considered in isolation from the impact they may have on existing provision and that there was no need for discussion with the wider community at that stage of the pr
defaultoceedings.
defaultFreedom of Information Requests (FoI)default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultGiven the paucity of information available about the decision-making process for approving a free school and the actual bids submitted by SbNAT and the Seckford Foundation, COMPASS sought to use Freedom of Information requests to elicit more detailed infor
defaultmation about the applications and approval process. However on a number of occasions, information requested via FoI was turned down on the grounds that it was not in the public interest, and still refused following further challenge. Unsuccessful FoIs incl
defaultuded: 
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaulta request in July 2011 to establish the evidence of demand contained in the SbNAT free school application;
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaulta request in October 2011 enquiring about the reasons the SbNAT bid was rejected;
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaulta request in April 2012 for the release of minutes, notes or
default action points from a meeting held in November 2011 to discuss free schools in Suffolk between DfE and Suffolk County Council (SCC) officials.  FoI was served to both DfE and SCC in this case; following appeal to both organisations the final response was t
defaulthat no notes or action points were recorded.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultResponses received from the DfE to our FoI requests served only to heighten our concerns about the lack of transparency in the free school application process, and raised further questions about the robustness o
defaultf the process.  The following extract is an example.  It is taken from the DfE response to an appeal about the refusal to release information about the reasons the SbNAT bid was rejected:
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default“
defaultThe panel also discussed the points raised in your email of 1 Janua
defaultry 2012.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
default‘
defaultIt is in the public interest to understand why a free school application has failed, because public money has been spent in the course of the process, and there is a general presumption that government should be open and transparent.
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIt is in the
default public interest to know the general reasons why free school applications have failed, as this is likely to be of use to other Free School applicants who can then adapt applications accordingly.
default’
defaultWe do not publish the reasons for failure of individual proj
defaultects because the process is competitive, where applications are compared against each other and a range of contextual information is taken account. This means that there is no minimum benchmark for an application to be successful because it is dependent on
default the number and quality of applications received within the round. This could potentially vary significantly from one round to the next. Therefore, releasing information about individual unsuccessful projects may be unhelpful to future applicants and could
default stifle innovative solutions.
default”
defaultNo democratic processdefault&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCOMPASS sought unsuccessfully to discuss our concerns with the DfE in 2011 and 2012. The DfE
default’
defaults position was that wider discussion about a free school would only be held if the application were through to the pre-opening stage. Given that pre-opening de facto implies that a school will open, this effectively renders invalid any local opposition to 
defaultthe proposal and severely limits any potential for democratic process. 
defaultImpact on Existing Schoolsdefault&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSuffolk is a relatively small LEA but has a significant surplus of secondary school places 
default–
default 
defaultparticularly in the areas in which free schools were proposed (o
defaultr have since opened).  This point was put to the DfE by the Local Authority. By 2016, given the existing level of surplus plus the provision of additional 11-16 free schools, nearly one third of the secondary school places planned for Suffolk will not be u
defaultsed. 
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThis is important because carrying a significant surplus of places leads to consequent burdens in cost, and reduces the cost-effectiveness of education spending in the authority overall. It should be noted that in Suffolk, per-capita funding at key s
defaulttage 4 is already lower than in other LEAs. 
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultLocal Authority data made it clear that an additional free school in Stoke by Nayland would add more surplus places, and place significant financial strain on existing schools, including GCUS, should pupils who 
defaultwere expected to attend existing schools instead go to the new free school. Through a consequent reduction in budget, this in turn would reduce the educational offer existing schools could make to their remaining pupils. Thus the opening of a free school i
defaultn a locality with surplus places could lead to a reduction in educational offer for all local pupils 
default–
default 
defaultas clearly acknowledged in the DfE
default’
defaults own impact assessment for Saxmundham Free School which was only recently made public.
defaultImpact on SOR default(N.B. Paragraph
defaults 24-26 concern the context in Suffolk, rather than the case of Stoke by Nayland 
defaultper se
default.)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe DfE inviting (and in some cases approving) applications for free schools in Suffolk at the same time the Local Authority was already undertaking a major reorganis
defaultation of schools in the county has complicated planning for the Authority, for schools and for local parents. It will also make it impossible to ascertain whether any future successes or failures are due to the advent of the free schools or the closure of 
defaultthe middle schools. This is because it has resulted in a piecemeal approach to raising standards in the county rather than a strategic response. 
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultThe free schools that have been opened in Suffolk (and the proposed one in Stoke by Nayland) are all small secondary schools. The DfE and Local Authority appear to hold contradictory views about the size of secondary schools: the Authority proposed 1200 pu
defaultpils as the optimum number for a school to be financially viable and offer a broad and balanced curriculum, yet the free school proposals have all been for schools of 540 pupils maximum.  
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultSuffolk is a rural county. Schools therefore rely on school transpo
defaultrt arrangements, responsibility for which remains with the Local Authority. The DfE required Local Authorities to provide transport to free schools, yet the process of approving free schools in Suffolk occurred without reference to the need for school plac
defaultes. This raises the very real possibility that the introduction of free schools in an area may reduce parental choice, not expand it, because parents in a rural area may need to make choice based on how their children will get to school.
defaultCONCLUSIONSdefault&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCOMPAS
defaultS was formed to promote public debate about a proposed free school and facilitate expression of local opposition to that proposal. It was formed because the Free School application process as it stands at present does not facilitate open dialogue with the 
defaultcommunity or proper public testing of proposals and the assumptions within them at an early enough stage. This includes, crucially, no open acknowledgement of the impact a new free school in a locality with surplus places could have on existing provision. 
defaultThus what could be an exercise in bringing together community stakeholders to support local schools instead becomes divisive and wasteful of resources.   
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultIn submitting this evidence to the Select Committee, COMPASS are hopeful that the Committee will cons
defaultider the need for more transparency and open debate as part of the Free Schools application process going forward. 
